ACT IV. Scmm I.

The poet conducts the plot with great judgment3 it grows more and more interesting as it proceeds, and raises our impatience to know the issue. A new scene is going to present itself. Phanium, s'o dear to Antipho, and whom he is so afraid of losing, turns out to be Chremes’ daughter, the very wife Demipho had intended for his son. All this we learn, not by a minute narration, which would have been tedious, but the poet has so contrived the conversation of the persons con- cerned, that by hints from them, and a little reflection, we understand the whole. This pleases the reader‚ as it leaves some employment for him, to trace the particulars of the story, and gives scope τό his fancy and imagination.
